@node features "PowerInstaller / Features"

 @{b} Features @{ub}

 PowerInstaller has some key featurs Commodore's Installer missed.
 Here there are brief (and uncomplete) list:

   @{fg shine}High Scalability@{fg text}

     PowerInstaller is designed to suit different kinds of
     installation process, from the full-featured CD-Rom
     installation (with graphics and Splash Windows) to
     the more modest single floppy disk installation.
     PowerInstaller interface adapts itself to the
     installation you need.

   @{fg shine}No MUI (Magical User Interface)@{fg text}

     Since PowerInstaller must be able to perform single
     floppy disk installations, PowerInstaller does not
     use MUI (which can eat up a lot of disk space).

   @{fg shine}Complete GUI Creation Control @{fg text}

     You can @{i}design@{ui} your GUI for your own needs.
     There is no @{i}built in@{ui} GUI structure, but you
     can add all the gadgets, strings, messages, checkboxes
     you want.

   @{fg shine}Splash Window Support @{fg text}

     PowerInstaller is able to display @{i}Splash Windows@{ui},
     a graphics windows you can use to show some features of the
     program you are installing.

   @{fg shine}GUI Images Support @{fg text}

     PowerInstaller can also show graphics inside the main window,
     letting you to add, for example, a graphic title to your
     installation.
     Both "Top" and "Side" images are supported.

   @{fg shine}Datatypes Support @{fg text}

     PowerInstaller can load all image formats supported by
     DataTypes system. So you can share your graphics for
     Splash Windows or GUI Images in JPEG, GIF or PNG format.

   @{fg shine}Resizable and Font Sensitive GUI @{fg text}

     PowerInstaller features a complete resizable and Font sensitive GUI.
     The window will be able to adapt itself to your GUI design.

   @{fg shine}Step-By-Step Installation Process@{fg text}

     PowerInstaller structures the installation process in a step-by-step
     way, so you can let the user get back on his choices, until the
     @{i}last@{ui} continue button is pressed.
     This idea is very good, since the user can revise his choices before
     starting installation.

   @{fg shine}Doesn't stop under errors@{fg text}

     PowerInstaller does not stop completely when an Installation error
     occurs. On the other hand, it let the user select wether to continue
     the installation process or not.

   @{fg shine}Complete UserStartup control@{fg text}

     PowerInstaller offers you all the tools you need to handle
     UserStartup entries.

   @{fg shine}Logfile Support@{fg text}

     PowerInstaller can save a log of all operations done, to allow
     smooth uninstallations.

   @{fg shine}AmigaOS3.0+ Only@{fg text}

     PowerInstaller has been developed with OS3.0 in mind.
     It will be upgraded to the new OS4 and OS5 when they'll
     be avaible.

   @{fg shine}Powerful Scripting Language@{fg text}

     PowerInstaller features a very powerful scripting language
     that allows you to create installation processes in a breeze.

   @{fg shine}Debug Mode Support@{fg text}

     PowerInstaller supports DEBUG mode, which will make PowerInstaller
     execute in a special fashion to help debug your installation processes.

@endnode

@node flowcont "PowerInstaller / Flow Control"

  @{b} Flow Control @{ub}

  @{fg shine} How to control Installation Flow @{fg text}

  PowerInstaller is currently offering very small support for
  Flow Control, simply because you should be able to let the
  user do exactly what *you* want with the tools provided.

  Anyway, you can make some decisions (assumptions) by checking
  variables with the @{" If " LINK if} clause.

  @{" If " LINK if} clause is very powerful and helps you
  showing to the user what you desire, masking all the rest.

  In the future betas, PowerInstaller will feature also some
  new keywords to help you controlling the installation process
  more closely.

@endnode

@node general "PowerInstaller / General Conventions"

  @{b} General Conventions @{ub}

  @{fg shine} The PowerInstaller Script Language @{fg text}

  PowerInstaller is a @{i}script interpreter@{ui}, which means that
  it takes an ASCII script as input, guiding the user through the
  installation process.

  The script is written in a custom language, called @{i}PowerInstaller Language@{ui}.
  To see the syntax of all commands avaible, please refer to @{" All PowerInstaller Commands " LINK all_commands}
  or to the @{" group sorted section " LINK grp_commands} always in this manual.

  Basically, what you need to know, is that each PowerInstaller command is based on the
  standard AmigaDOS ReadArgs() system call, so params follow the standard ReadArgs() conventions.
  This means that you are not binded to one single way of writing things, because you
  can use all the ReadArgs() features in your own PowerInstaller sources.

  So, for example: the @{" Define " LINK define} command, used to define a new variable,
  has this syntax (or @{i}Template@{ui}):

    DEFINE  VARNAME/A,VALUE/A


  so, to define a var called "NewVariable" with "Hello World" in it,
  you can write this:

    Define  NewVariable "Hello World"

  but also this would do the work:

    Define  "Hello World" VARNAME NewVariable


  To know everything about variable handling, please refer to @{" Variable Support " LINK varsupport} section.


@endnode

@node guicreation "PowerInstaller / GUI Creation"

  @{b} The GUI Creation System @{ub}

  PowerInstaller divides the installation process into @{i}Pages@{ui}
  of choices the user has to do to make a good installation.
  To allow the PowerInstaller Script creator to have a nice and easy
  method to create Installation Scripts, PowerInstaller features the
  concept of @{i}GUI/Pages@{ui}.

  A @{i}GUI/Page@{ui} is a section of @{" PowerInstaller Language " LINK all_commands} lines
  between @{" BeginGUI " LINK begingui} and @{" EndGUI " LINK endgui}.

  Inside these two commands, you can put all PowerInstaller GUI commands, such as
  @{" Message " LINK message}, @{" Radio " LINK radio}, @{" Check " LINK check} and so on.

  When the command @{" EndGUI " LINK endgui} will be called, the GUI will be
  prompted to the user, so he/she can make his/her choices.

  @{fg shine} Hello World! @{fg text}

  Here there is the smallest code you can write in PowerInstaller: the "Hello World"
  script:

  @{" BeginGUI  " LINK begingui} Main
    @{" Message " LINK message} "Hello World!"
  @{" EndGUI    " LINK endgui}

  (See the working script in PowerInstaller/DemoScripts/HelloWorld.script)


  @{fg shine} Check this out! @{fg text}

  As soon as you need the user to iteract with you, you should also
  have him/her making choices. PowerInstaller features a lot of ways to
  create a GUI asking for user feedback, here we'll examine the
  @{" Check " LINK check} command.
  You can create a list of Check boxes in your GUI, by simply adding one
  @{" Check " LINK check} command after another.

  See this script:

  @{" Define    " LINK define} Var1 0
  @{" Define    " LINK define} Var2 0
  @{" Define    " LINK define} Var3 0

  @{" BeginGUI  " LINK begingui} Main

    @{" Check   " LINK check} "Variable 1" Var1 $Var1
    @{" Check   " LINK check} "Variable 2" Var2 $Var2
    @{" Check   " LINK check} "Variable 3" Var3 $Var3

  @{" EndGUI    " LINK endgui}

  @{" BeginGUI  " LINK begingui} Choices

    @{" Message " LINK message} "Var1 is $Var1"
    @{" Message " LINK message} "Var2 is $Var2"
    @{" Message " LINK message} "Var3 is $Var3"

  @{" EndGUI    " LINK endgui}

  (You can find this script in "PowerInstaller/DemoScripts/CheckThisOut.script")


  @{fg shine} Radio Gaga  @{fg text}

  The @{" Radio " LINK radio} command works in a very similar way:

  @{" BeginGUI  " LINK begingui} Main

    @{" Message " LINK message} "Please, select one option!"

    @{" Radio   " LINK radio} "Option 0"
    @{" Radio   " LINK radio} "Option 1"
    @{" Radio   " LINK radio} "Option 2"

  @{" EndGUI    " LINK endgui}

  @{" BeginGUI  " LINK begingui} results

    @{" Message " LINK message} "Option chosen: $Result"

  @{" EndGUI    " LINK endgui}

  (The working script is in "PowerInstaller/DemoScripts/RadioGAGA.script"}

@endnode

@node all_commands "PowerInstaller / Commands"

  @{b} PowerInstaller Commands @{ub}

    @{" AddPath           " LINK addpath         } Adds a path to another
    @{" AddUserStartup    " LINK adduserstartup  } Adds text to the @{" UserStartup Code " LINK userstartup}
    @{" AskPath           " LINK askpath         } Draws a Path Requester in the GUI
    @{" BeginGUI          " LINK begingui        } Starts GUI definition
    @{" Call              " LINK call            } Calls a proc
    @{" Check             " LINK check           } Draws a CheckBox gadget in the GUI
!   @{" ClearLog          " LINK clearlog        } Clears Installation Log
!   @{" CollectFiles      " LINK collectfiles    } Collect file list inside an archive
!   @{" CopyFile          " LINK copyfile        } Copies a single file
!D  @{" DumpFiles         " LINK dumpfiles       } Dumps all files to install on the console
    @{" Define            " LINK define          } Defines a new Variable
    @{" DiskSpace         " LINK diskspace       } Returns avaible space on a device
    @{" EndGUI            " LINK endgui          } Draws a GUI on the screen
!   @{" Execute           " LINK execute         } Executes an AmigaDOS calls
    @{" Exit              " LINK exit            } Exits from the installation process
    @{" Extract           " LINK extract         } Extracts one or more files from the archive
    @{" EZReq             " LINK ezreq           } Shows an EasyRequetser (ReqTools)
    @{" FilePart          " LINK filepart        } Returns the file name inside a path
    @{" If / Else / EndIf " LINK IF              } If Block
    @{" Image             " LINK image           } Changes Border and Top images
    @{" Installer         " LINK installer       } Checks/sets some PowerInstaller features
!   @{" InstallFiles      " LINK installfiles    } Begins installation process for real
    @{" MakeAssign        " LINK makeassign      } Creates a new assign
    @{" Message           " LINK message         } Shows a message on the GUI
    @{" ParentDir         " LINK parentdir       } Returns the parent dir of the provided path
    @{" PathPart          " LINK pathpart        } Returns the path of the given path
    @{" Processor         " LINK processor       } Returns the user Amiga 680x0 processor
    @{" Radio             " LINK radio           } Draws a Radio button on the GUI
!   @{" SaveLog           " LINK savelog         } Saves a log file
    @{" SearchAssign      " LINK searchassign    } Searches for a specific assign
!   @{" SelectFiles       " LINK selectfiles     } Shows a list of avaible files
    @{" Set               " LINK set             } Sets a variable to a given value
    @{" SetArchive        " LINK setarchive      } Sets working archive
!   @{" SplashWindow      " LINK splashwindow    } Opens a Splash Window with gfx inside
    @{" StrAdd            " LINK stradd          } Adds a string to another
    @{" StrCopy           " LINK strcopy         } Copies a string into another
!   @{" Text              " LINK text            } Creates a String Gadget
    @{" Version           " LINK version         } Returns version and revision of a file
    @{" WriteUserStartup  " LINK writeuserstartup} Writes @{" UserStartup Code " LINK userstartup} on disk


@endnode

