@node intro "PowerInstaller / Introduction"

  @{b} Introduction @{ub}

  Welcome to a new era in the history of Amiga installers.

  After ages of Commodore Installer, now a new, powerful
  tool has come to life, just to help you creating even more
  attacting, reliable and fast SetUp procedures.

  PowerInstaller comes to life after a long and accurate study
  of the Amiga users needs, trying to satisfy and match all the
  requests a user can have during the Installation process, yet
  keeping an eye also on programmer, who has the hard duty of writing
  a good, easy to use, Installer script.

  PowerInstaller is something which tries to match both these requests.
  It is powerful, reliable and incredibly flexible, but it is also
  easy to use, easy to program... and make SetUp processes a breeze for
  the users.

  Even unexperienced users will gain advantages in the use of this new
  PowerInstaller, which will allow anyone to get back in the installation
  process, without problems.

  PowerInstaller is my final word to Installation programs for the Amiga.
  It is a very good program, IMHO. I hope you'll like it and use it to
  install your programs.
  It is also completely free, but please, take your time to read the
  @{" Copyrights " LINK copyright} conditions.

  This is another gift of mine to the Amiga Community.

  May the Force be with you... always.


              Fabio Rotondo

@endnode

@node howtouse "PowerInstaller / How To Use"

  @{b} How To Use @{ub}

  PowerInstaller is, like the Commodore Installer, a script interpreter.

  It has some new and powerful features, Commodore's one missed, anyway.

  The language is very easy to use, far more easy than Commodore's one,
  and you'll learn it step by step, looking in this guide file for the
  reference of every command, each time you'll need it.

  Every command is, in fact, an AmigaDOS ReadArgs() Template, so you'll see
  that params are presented with usual /A, /S ... flags, giving you a
  feeling of standard things :-)

  There are some things you @{b}must@{ub} know to start writing PowerInstaller
  script. Please, follow these steps, and you'll never have any problem.

  Please, read:

    @{" Variable Support    " LINK varsupport}
    @{" General Conventions " LINK general}
    @{" GUI Creation        " LINK guicreation}
    @{" Flow Control        " LINK flowcont}
    @{" System Variables    " LINK sysvar}

@endnode

