@node varsupport "PowerInstaller / Variable Support"

  @{b} Variable Support @{ub}

  PowerInstaller features the support of variables.

  You can define @{i}global@{ui} and @{i}local@{ui} variables,
  depending on your needs and on the scope you intend to give
  to a single variable.

  --

  @{b} Overview @{ub}

  Typically, variables contain string values, and also the numbers are
  considered strings.
  You cannot set a variable to contain a numeric value, because it will
  be translated into a string. So keep in mind this.
  Anyway, this isn't a very bad limit, you'll learn why.

  @{b}NOTE:@{ub} in PowerInstaller parsing system, UPPERCASE and lowercase
        variable names are just the same...

    @{b} The @{" Define " LINK define} instruction @{ub}

    In order to use a new variable in your scripts, you have to @{i}define@{ui} it.
    Declaration will create the new variable in the list of avaible variables, assigning
    it a starting value.

    If you try to set a certain value to a var that hasn't been defined, you'll receive
    an error message.

    Please, refer to the @{" Define " LINK define} syntax to know how to create
    a new variable.

      @{b}NOTE:@{ub}
      you can @{i}turn off@{ui} variable declaration using the @{" Installer " LINK installer} instruction.


    @{b} The @{" Set " LINK set} instruction @{ub}

    Once a certain variable exists for the PowerInstaller, you can change its
    value, using the @{" Set " LINK set} instruction.

    Please, refer to the @{" Set " LINK set} syntax to know how to set a certain
    value inside a variable.


    @{b} How to read variable contents @{ub}

    To read, or @{i}get@{ui}, the contents of a variable, you just have to
    add a "$" char in front of the variable name. This thing works with every
    PowerInstaller command.

  --

  @{b} Working Example @{ub}

    Please, see: @{" Variable Handling Demo Script " LINK demo_var}

@endnode

@node demo_var "PowerInstaller / Variable Handling Demo Script"

  @{b} Variable Handling Demo Script @{ub}

  In the following example, we'll show you how to define, set and read the value
  inside a variable.

  ; PowerInstaller Demo Script

  @{" Define  " LINK define} First    "Fabio"
  @{" Define  " LINK define} Last     "Rotondo"

  ; Please, note how the FullName is set to "Fabio Rotondo"...

  @{" Define  " LINK define} FullName "$First $Last"


  ; Here we open a GUI

  @{" BeginGUI " LINK begingui} main

    @{" Message  " LINK message} "The full name is $FullName"
    @{" Message  " LINK message} "The first name is $First"
    @{" Message  " LINK message} "The last name is $Last"

  ; Note: we are going to change First contents

    @{" Set      " LINK set    } First "Changed"

    @{" Message  " LINK message} "Now First value is $First"

  @{" EndGUI   " LINK endgui}

@endnode

@node sysvar "PowerInstaller / System Variables"

  @{b} System Variables @{ub}

  PowerInstaller comes with some System Variables, which are some vars
  that you will use inside your PowerInstaller scripts, often without
  knowing it...

  Each System Var has its default value, you can change using the
  standard PowerInstaller @{" Set " LINK set} command.

  There are two different kinds of System Variables:

    @{b} GUI/Localization Variables @{ub}

    These are variables storing the text that will appear on the
    PowerInstaller GUIs. You can set these variables to change
    the text of the gadgets. So, for example, you could localize
    a GUI by simply refine these vars.

    GUI/Localization Variables are:


      VARIABLE NAME   |    DEFAULT VALUE            | DESCRIPTION
    ------------------+-----------------------------+----------------------------
      Abort_Gadgets   | Continue Installation|Abort | Gadgets for Abort Requester
      Abort_Message   | Are you sure you want to    | Message for the Abort Req.
                      | abort\nthe current          |
                      | installation?               |
      Abort_Title     | Abort Confirmation          | Title for the Abort Req.
    ------------------+-----------------------------+----------------------------
      Gadget_Cancel   | Cancel                      | Gadget "Cancel" Text
      Gadget_GetPath  | R                           | Gadget for browsing
      Gadget_Help     | Help                        | Gadget "Help" Text
      Gadget_Next     | Next >                      | Gadget "Next >" Text
      Gadget_Path     | Path:                       | Gadget "Path:" Text
      Gadget_Prev     | < Prev                      | Gadget "< Prev" Text
      Gadget_CreateDir| Create New Dir              | Gadget "Create New Dir"
    ------------------+-----------------------------+----------------------------
      Path_Title      | Select Path                 | Title of Path Requester



    @{b} System Variables   @{ub}

    These are special variables, which tell to PowerInstaller important
    things, like which Dearchive program to use and which is its syntax or so.

    System Variables are:

      VARIABLE NAME   |    DEFAULT VALUE            | DESCRIPTION
    ------------------+-----------------------------+----------------------------
      Result          | 0                           | Here we store last result
    ------------------+-----------------------------+----------------------------
      Extractor       | Lha                         | Name of the Archive extr.
      Extract_Dir     | -r -q e                     | Syntax to extract a dir
      Extract_File    | -q e                        | Syntax to extract a file
      Extract_List    | vq                          | Syntax to extract a list of files
      Extract_Skip    | 3                           | Lines to "avoid" before getting the list
      Extract_Position| 0                           | Where the word is

@endnode

@node "installer" "PowerInstaller Commands: Installer"

           NAME: Installer

       SYNOPSIS: Installer VERSION,REVISION,DEF/S,NODEF/S,DEBUG/S

    DESCRIPTION: Use this command to set/check some of PowerInstaller features.

          INPUT: VERSION      - Use this to check if PowerInstaller version is equal
                                or later the value you provide.

                 REVISION     - Same of VERSION, but for REVISION.

                 DEF/S        - It is a swicth. By providing this, PowerInstaller
                                will require you to @{" Define " LINK "define"} a
                                variable before you can use it.

                 NODEF/S      - Another switch. By providing this, you will not need
                                to @{" Define " LINK define} variables anymore.

                 DEBUG/S      - Providing this swith, PowerInstaller will be issued
                                in DEBUG mode. A small requester will appear when
                                starting the program, just to remind you to remove
                                DEBUG switch before distribuiting the installation
                                procedure.

        RESULTS: NONE

       EXAMPLES: - Installer 2 0

                   PowerInstaller will throw an error if the version you are using is
                   not V2.0 or later)

                 - Installer 1 DEF

                   Will check against Version 1.0 and will require variable definitions.

       SEE ALSO: @{" Define " LINK define}
@endnode

@node "message" "PowerInstaller Commands: Message"

           NAME: Message

       SYNOPSIS: Message TEXT/A

    DESCRIPTION: Use this command to add a message line to the current message.

          INPUT: TEXT     - The text message.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - Message "Hello World!"

                   Will display "Hello World" in the GUI.

       SEE ALSO: @{" General Conventions " LINK general}
                 @{" EZReq               " LINK ezreq}
@endnode

@node "set" "PowerInstaller Commands: set"

           NAME: Set

       SYNOPSIS: Set  VARNAME/A,VALUE/A

    DESCRIPTION: Sets the value of the variable called VARNAME to the provided one.

          INPUT: VARNAME        - Name of the variable.
                                  If may throw an error if you provide
                                  a wrong variable name.
                                  See: @{" Installer " LINK installer} for info.

                 VALUE          - Value to assign.
                                  NOTE: it is a string expression.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - Set Name "Fabio"

                   Set to the variable Name, the value Fabio.

                 - Set MyName $Name

                   Set to the variable MyName, the _value_ contained in the Name variable.

                 - Set MyName "My Name is $Name"

                   Will set MyName to "My Name is Fabio"

       SEE ALSO: @{" Define " LINK define}
@endnode

@node "define" "PowerInstaller Commands: define"

           NAME: Define

       SYNOPSIS: Define  VARNAME/A,VALUE/A,GLOBAL/S

    DESCRIPTION: Defines a new variable.

          INPUT: VARNAME        - Name of the variable.

                 VALUE          - Starting Value.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - Define Name "Fabio"

                   Define the new variable Name, with the value Fabio.

                 - Define MyName $Name

                   Define the variable MyName, assigning the value of Name variable.

                 - Define MyName "My Name is $Name"

                   Will define MyName with the value "My Name is Fabio"

       SEE ALSO: @{" Set " LINK set}
@endnode

@node "EZReq" "PowerInstaller Commands: EZReq"

           NAME: EZReq

       SYNOPSIS: EZReq  TEXT/A,GADS/A,TITLE

    DESCRIPTION: Create a standard ReqTools Easy requester.

          INPUT: TEXT/A     - The text to show

                 GADS/A     - Gadgets to provide

                 TITLE      - (Optional) Requester title.

        RESULTS: the resulting choice of the user is stored in the
                 'Result' variable.

       EXAMPLES: - EZReq "This is a test" "I Know|Bye"

                   Show a requester.

                 - EZReq "Press 1 2 or 0" "1|2|0"
                   Message "You pressed: $Result"

                   Show a requester and prompt the result.

       SEE ALSO: @{" Message " LINK message}
@endnode

@node "image" "PowerInstaller Commands: Image"

           NAME: Image

       SYNOPSIS: Image  IMAGENAME,TOPIMAGE

    DESCRIPTION: Set the new image for the border or for the top of the
                 Installer window.

                 On every Installer GUI you can have two images:

                  IMAGENAME is the pic that will appear on the left of the
                            Installer window

                  TOPIMAGE  is the pic that will appear on the top of the
                            Installer window.

                 Since there is no size limit for these two images, please
                 try to keep them as small as possible, so that they can
                 fit on any user's Workbench screen.


          INPUT: IMAGENAME      - Path of the BorderPic

                 TOPIMAGE       - Path of the Top picture.

        RESULTS:


          NOTES: - To optimize loading times, these two pictures are stored
                   from one GUI to the next one, so, if you don't want to change
                   them on every installation step, you can just set them at the
                   beginning of the Installer script.

                 - Image loading supports DataTypes.

       EXAMPLES: - Image "Bordpic.iff"

                   Will set "Bordpic.iff" as the new BorderPic.

                 - Image TOPIMAGE "TopPic.iff"

                   Sets the "TopPic.iff" as the new top pic.

                 - Image "Bordpic.iff" $TopFile

                   Will use BordPic.iff for the border pic and the
                   content of the TopFile variable to show the TopPic.

       SEE ALSO: @{" SplashWindow " LINK splashwindow}
@endnode

@node "begingui" "PowerInstaller Commands: BeginGUI"

           NAME: BeginGUI

       SYNOPSIS: BeginGUI NAME/A

    DESCRIPTION: This is the new GUI window definition.

          INPUT: NAME/A     - This is an unique name you MUST assing to
                              every GUI window, to allow jump in the script
                              using @{" ShowGUI " LINK "showgui"} command.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - BeginGUI "Welcome"

                   Starts the creation of the Welcome GUI.

       SEE ALSO: @{" EndGUI " LINK endgui}
@endnode

@node "radio" "PowerInstaller Commands: Radio"

           NAME: Radio

       SYNOPSIS: Radio  TEXT,VAR

    DESCRIPTION: Create a new Radio button.

                 You can add several Radio commands together to
                 create a Radio button choices window.
                 For example, to prompt for the installation kind:

                  Message "Select Installation:"

                  Radio   "Typical"
                  Radio   "Full"
                  Radio   "Minimal"
                  Radio   "Custom"
                  Radio   VAR RadioChoice



          INPUT: TEXT       - (Optional) Text of the Radio button

                 VAR        - (Optional) Name of the Var where to
                              store the result. If it is omitted,
                              the result will be saved in the Result
                              variable, anyway.

           NOTE: - If you provide the variable, the starting value
                   of the Radio list will be the value contained in
                   the var you provided.

        RESULTS:

       SEE ALSO: @{" Check " LINK check}
                 @{" Radio " LINK radio}
@endnode

@node "askpath" "PowerInstaller Commands: askpath"

           NAME: AskPath

       SYNOPSIS: AskPath  DESTVAR/A

    DESCRIPTION: Creates a custom Path requester.

                 This command creates a custom Path requester in the
                 PowerInstaller GUI window.
                 It is the typical requester prompting for a path
                 with a string gadget and with a button, showing a
                 standard ReqTools Path Requester.


          INPUT: DESTVAR    - The name of the var where to place the
                              result into.

        RESULTS:


          NOTES: - The starting path will be set to the path contained in
                   the provided DESTVAR.

                 - You can change these messages with these variables:

                    MESSAGE       | VARNAME
                    --------------+----------------------
                    'Path:'       | Gadget_Path
                    'R'           | Gadget_GetPath
                    'Select Path' | Path_Title


       EXAMPLES: - AskPath  DestDir

                   Will place the result in DestDir var.

       SEE ALSO: @{" System Variables " LINK sysvar}
@endnode

@node "addpath" "PowerInstaller Commands: AddPath"

           NAME: AddPath

       SYNOPSIS: AddPath  VAR/A,NEWPART/A

    DESCRIPTION: This command adds a new part to the current
                 path stored in the VAR provided.
                 This is a front end for the AddPart() AmigaDOS call.

          INPUT: VAR/A      - Name of the variable.

                 NEWPART/A  - New part of path to add to the VAR.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - Set      Path "Ram:"
                   AddPath  Path "T"

                   The Path var will be set to "Ram:T"

                 - Set      Path "Ram:T"
                   AddPath  Path "TempDir"

                   The Path var will be set to "Ram:T/TempDir"

       SEE ALSO: @{" AskPath " LINK askpath}
@endnode

@node "check" "PowerInstaller Commands: Check"

           NAME: Check

       SYNOPSIS: Check TEXT/A,VAR/A,VALUE

    DESCRIPTION: This command will create a CheckBox gadget in the
                 new GUI. Each CheckBox *MUST* be associated to a
                 variable used to store the final result.
                 You can provide a default value, using the VALUE
                 tag. Even if it is optional, I suggest you to use
                 the same value of the VAR variable, so that the
                 CheckBox will reflect the VAR value.
                 See examples below.

          INPUT: TEXT/A     - Text of the CheckBox gadget.

                 VAR/A      - Name of the variable where to store
                              the result.

                 VALUE      - (Optional) Starting value.

        RESULTS:

           NOTE: Even if you have chosen not to @{" Define " LINK define}
                 your variables, the VAR/A you want to use to store the
                 result must exists.

       EXAMPLES: - Check "Test 1" Test1 $Test1
                   Check "Test 2" Test2 $Test2

                   Will show "Test1" and "Test2" CheckBoxes and will
                   store the result in the Test1/2 vars.

       SEE ALSO: @{" Radio " LINK radio}
                 @{" Text  " LINK text}
@endnode

@node "if" "PowerInstaller Commands: If ... Else ... EndIf"

           NAME: If ... Else ... EndIf - Block Condition

       SYNOPSIS: IF FIRSTVAL/A,SECONDVAL/A,NOT/S,EQUAL/S,MAJOR/S

    DESCRIPTION: This is the If...Else...EndIf block condition
                 very similar to a lot of If/else/endif languages.

                 Please, follow these rules:

                 - If MUST be built of TWO values that will be
                   compared.

                 - Every If *MUST* be closed by an EndIf statement.

          INPUT: FIRSTVAL/A   - First value to check.

                 SECONDVAL/A  - Second value to check.

                 NOT/S        - The If condition will be true if the
                                desired condition is NOT true.

                 EQUAL/S      - Check IF FIRSTVAL is EQUAL TO SECONDVAL.

                 MAJOR/S      - Check IF FIRSTVAL is greater than SECONDVAL.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - If $Test1 EQUAL 0

                   Will be true if Test1 var is equal to 0.

                 - If $Test1 EQUAL $Test2

                   Will be true if Test1 is equal to Test2.

       SEE ALSO:
@endnode

@node "SetArchive" "PowerInstaller Commands: SetArchive"

           NAME: SetArchive

       SYNOPSIS: SetArchive ARCHIVENAME/A

    DESCRIPTION: Use this command to set the archive name
                 where all archive operations will be performed.
                 Typically, this is the installation archive.

          INPUT: ARCHIVENAME/A  - The name of the archive.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - SetArchive "WebFX.lha"

                   Will set work archive to "WebFX.lha"

       SEE ALSO: @{" Extract      " LINK extract}
                 @{" SetFiles     " LINK setfiles}
                 @{" SelectFiles  " LINK selectfiles}
@endnode

@node "searchassign" "PowerInstaller Commands: SearchAssign"

           NAME: SearchAssign

       SYNOPSIS: SearchAssign ASSIGN/A,DESTVAR/A,DEFVAL/A,PARENT/S

    DESCRIPTION: This command will search the Assigns for the desired
                 assign and will place the result in the provided
                 var (DESTVAR). If the Assign isn't found, then the
                 value contained in DEFVAL is used.

                 With the PARENT switch set, it will return the
                 parent path of the dir returned by the Assign.
                 This is useful if you want to be placed in the
                 dir BEFORE your default installation dir, for example
                 if you have to perform an upgrade of the program.

                 See examples below.


          INPUT: ASSIGN/A   - Name of the assign to search.

                 DESTVAR/A  - Variable where to store the result.

                 DEFVAL/A   - Default value to assign to DESTVAR if the
                              assign isn't found.

                 PARENT/S   - Get the parent directory (only if the Assign
                              exists and the DEFVAL is not used).

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - SearchAssign "WebFX:" DestDir "Work:WebFX"

                   If the "WebFX:" assign does not exists, it will
                   return "Work:WebFX"

                 - SearchAssign "WebFX:" DestDir $DestDir PARENT

                   If the "WebFX:" assign _exists_ it will return "Work:"
                   (because the PARENT) switch is set.

       SEE ALSO:
@endnode

@node "extract" "PowerInstaller Commands: Extract"

           NAME: Extract

       SYNOPSIS: Extract DESTDIR/A,FILES/A

    DESCRIPTION: This command will extract the provided FILES
                 in the desired dir.

                 Please, note that Extract is a _generic_ command,
                 and that PowerInstaller does not know interally HOW
                 the extractor works.

                 See: @{" How Extract Works " LINK extract_works}

          INPUT: DESTDIR/A    - Destination directory where the
                                files will be extracted

                 FILES/A      - One or more file to extract from
                                the archive

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - Extract $DestDir "Docs/#?"

                   Extract all files under the Docs dir in the archive
                   into DestDir path.

       SEE ALSO: @{" SetArchive " LINK setarchive}
@endnode

@node "parentdir" "PowerInstaller Commands: ParentDir"

           NAME: ParentDir

       SYNOPSIS: ParentDir DIR/A,DESTVAR/A

    DESCRIPTION: This command will return the parent dir of the
                 given path.

                 NOTE: this command relies on Lock() AmigaDOS call.
                       So if the dir does not exists, DESTVAR will
                       be set to '' (empty string)


          INPUT: DIR/A      - Start directory

                 DESTVAR/A  - Variable where to store the result of
                              the ParentDir command.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - ParentDir  "Work:WebFX" DestDir

                   Will return "Work:" in DestDir.

       SEE ALSO:
@endnode

@node "makeassign" "PowerInstaller Commands: MakeAssign"

           NAME: MakeAssign

       SYNOPSIS: MakeAssign ASSIGN/A,PATH/A,REMOVE/S

    DESCRIPTION: This command will create the assign called ASSIGN,
                 giving it the PATH you'll provide.
                 The assign will become avaible in the standard assign
                 list immediately, and the UserStartUp code will
                 be modified to store this command.

          INPUT: ASSIGN/A   - Name of the assign.

                 PATH/A     - Path of the assign.

                 REMOVE/S   - If set, the assign will be removed.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - MakeAssign "WebFX:" "Work:WebFX"

                   Will assign "WebFX:" to "Work:WebFX"

                 - MakeAssign "WebFX:" $DestDir

                   Will assign "WebFX:" to the path stored in DestDir.

       SEE ALSO: @{" AddUserStartup " LINK adduserstartup}
@endnode

@node "adduserstartup" "PowerInstaller Commands: AddUserStartup"

           NAME: AddUserStartup

       SYNOPSIS: AddUserStartup TEXT/M

    DESCRIPTION: This command will add a text line into the
                 @{" UserStartup Code " LINK userstartup}.

                 This text will be saved to the s:User-Startup
                 file, if you'll call the @{" WriteUserStartup " LINK writeuserstartup} command.

          INPUT: TEXT/M     - Text to add to the @{" UserStartup Code" LINK userstartup}

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - AddUserStartup "; This is just a comment line"

                   Will add the message in the @{" UserStartup Code" LINK userstartup}.

       SEE ALSO: @{" WriteUserStartup " LINK writeuserstartup}
                 @{" UserStartUp Code " LINK userstartup}

@endnode

@node "writeuserstartup" "PowerInstaller Commands: WriteUserStartup"

           NAME: WriteUserStartup

       SYNOPSIS: WriteUserStartup SECTION/A,NEWFILE

    DESCRIPTION: This command will save the @{" UserStartup Code " LINK userstartup}
                 inside the User-Startup file, or, alternatively, into another
                 file provided by NEWFILE.

          INPUT: SECTION/A  - Name of the section.
                              (A section is delimited by

                                ;BEGIN section name

                                ;END

                               lines)


                 NEWFILE    - if you provide this param, the
                              @{" UserStartup Code " LINK userstartup} will be
                              saved in the provided filename, and not in the
                              standard User-Startup.

        RESULTS:

           NOTE: - If you provide the NEWFILE param, the file will be overwritten.

                 - If you *don't* provide the NEWFILE param, only the section
                   will be rewritten.


       EXAMPLES: - WriteUserStartup "WebFX"

                   Updates the User-Startup with the WebFX section.

                 - WriteUserStartup "WebFX" "Ram:WebFX_Startup"

                   Will save the @{" UserStartup Code " LINK userstartup} in the
                   WebFX_Startup file.

       SEE ALSO: @{" AddUserStartup   " LINK adduserstartup}

                 @{" UserStartup Code " LINK userstartup}
@endnode

@node "endgui" "PowerInstaller Commands: EndGUI"

           NAME: EndGUI

       SYNOPSIS: EndGUI

    DESCRIPTION: This command will create the last GUI defined AND will display it
                 on the screen.

          INPUT: NONE

        RESULTS:


       EXAMPLES: - BeginGUI Hello
                     Message "Hello World!"
                   EndGUI

                   Display a GUI with "Hello World!" in it.

       SEE ALSO: @{" BeginGUI " LINK begingui}
@endnode

@node "pathpart" "PowerInstaller Commands: PathPart"

           NAME: PathPart

       SYNOPSIS: PathPart PATH/A,VAR/A

    DESCRIPTION: This command will put inside var VAR/A the full path of the
                 given PATH/A string.

                 Eg. the PathPart of "Ram:T/Test" is "Ram:T/"

                 This command is similar to AmigaDOS System Call PathPart().

          INPUT: PATH/A       - Path to work on.

                 VAR/A        - Name of dest var.


        RESULTS:

           NOTE: - The last "/" char is leaved to better show it is a path.

       EXAMPLES: - PathPart "Ram:T/Test/Hello" Path

                   Path will contain "Ram:T/Test/"

       SEE ALSO: @{" FilePart   " LINK filepart}
@endnode

@node "filepart" "PowerInstaller Commands: filePart"

           NAME: FilePart

       SYNOPSIS: FilePart PATH/A,VAR/A

    DESCRIPTION: This command will put inside var VAR/A the name of the file
                 contained in the PATH/A string.

                 Eg. the FilePart of "Ram:T/Test" is "Test"

                 This command is similar to AmigaDOS System Call FilePart().

          INPUT: PATH/A       - Path to work on.

                 VAR/A        - Name of dest var.


        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - FilePart "Ram:T/Test/Hello" Name

                   Name will contain "Hello"

       SEE ALSO: @{" PathPart   " LINK pathpart}
@endnode

@node "strcopy" "PowerInstaller Commands: StrCopy"

           NAME: StrCopy

       SYNOPSIS: StrCopy DESTSTR/A,SOURCESTR/A,NUMCHARS

    DESCRIPTION: This command will copy the string SOURCESTR into the
                 destination variable DESTSTR.
                 You can also copy just NUMCHARS of the source string
                 and not the complete string.

          INPUT: DESTSTR/A    - Destination variable name

                 SOURCESTR/A  - Source String

                 NUMCHARS     - (Optional) Number of chars to copy.


        RESULTS:


       EXAMPLES: - StrCopy DestStr  $Name

                   Will copy the contents of variable Name into DestStr

                 - StrCopy DestStr  "Hello World"

                   Will copy "Hello World" into DestStr

       SEE ALSO: @{" StrAdd " LINK stradd}
@endnode

@node "stradd" "PowerInstaller Commands: StrAdd"

           NAME: StrAdd

       SYNOPSIS: StrAdd DESTSTR/A,SOURCESTR/A,NUMCHARS

    DESCRIPTION: This command will add the string SOURCESTR to the DESTSTR.
                 You can also add just NUMCHARS of the source string
                 and not the complete string.

          INPUT: DESTSTR/A    - Destination variable name

                 SOURCESTR/A  - Source String

                 NUMCHARS     - (Optional) Number of chars to add.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - StrAdd DestStr  $Name

                   Will add the contents of variable Name into DestStr

                 - StrAdd DestStr  "Hello World"

                   Will add "Hello World" into DestStr

       SEE ALSO: @{" StrCopy " LINK stradd}
@endnode

@node "processor" "PowerInstaller Commands: StrAdd"

           NAME: Processor

       SYNOPSIS: Processor VARNAME/A

    DESCRIPTION: This command will place inside VARNAME
                 the user's Amiga 680x0 processor.

          INPUT: VARNAME/A    - Name of the var where to store
                                the value.

        RESULTS: VARNAME will be filled with one of these strings:

                    68000     - Plain Motorola 68000
                    68010
                    68020
                    68030
                    68040     - Motorola 68040 without FPU
                    68040 FPU - Motorola 68040 WITH FPU
                    68060     - No comments.

       EXAMPLES: - Processor CPU

                   Var CPU will contain your processor.

       SEE ALSO:
@endnode

@node "diskspace" "PowerInstaller Commands: DiskSpace"

           NAME: DiskSpace

       SYNOPSIS: DiskSpace DRIVE/A, VAR

    DESCRIPTION: This command will return disk space currently
                 avaible on a device.

          INPUT: DRIVE/A      - The name of the device to check.

                 VAR          - Variable where to hold the result.

        RESULTS: The variable Result will hold the avaible disk space too.

       EXAMPLES: - DiskSpace "Work:" SPACE

                   SPACE will be filled with all the space avaible on "Work:"

       SEE ALSO:
@endnode

@node "version" "PowerInstaller Commands: Version"

           NAME: Version

       SYNOPSIS: Version FILE/A, VARVER/A, VARREV/A, LIBRARY/S

    DESCRIPTION: This command will fill VARVER and VARREV with
                 version and revision values of the file FILE.
                 You can specify the flag LIBRARY if you are going
                 to check version and revision of a library.

          INPUT: VARVER       - Variable where to store the version.

                 VARREV       - Variable where to store the revision.

                 LIBRARY      - It's a flag. Set this if you are going
                                to check for a particular library version.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - Version "reqtools.library" VER REV LIBRARY

                   Will fill VER and REV with you own "reqtools.library" version.

                 - Version "PowerInstaller" VER REV

                   Will tell you more about PowerInstaller

       SEE ALSO:
@endnode

@node "splashwindow" "PowerInstaller Commands: SplashWindow"

           NAME: SplashWindow

       SYNOPSIS: SplashWindow FILE/A,XPOS,YPOS

    DESCRIPTION: This command will open a borderless window
                 at the given X,Y position (or 0,0 if you omit them)
                 containing the image file.



          INPUT: FILE/A       - (Needed) The image file to show.

                 XPOS         - Starting X Position of the Splash Window

                 YPOS         - Starting Y Position of the Splash Window

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - SplashWindow "Splash/Splash1.iff"

                   Will open a window with the file "Splash1.iff"

       SEE ALSO: @{" Image " LINK image}
@endnode

@node "Text" "PowerInstaller Commands: Text"

           NAME: Text

       SYNOPSIS: Text TEXT/A,VAR/A,VALUE

    DESCRIPTION: This command will create a String gadget in the
                 new GUI. Each String gadget *MUST* be associated to a
                 variable used to store the final result.
                 You can provide a default value, using the VALUE
                 tag. Even if it is optional, I suggest you to use
                 the same value of the VAR variable, so that the
                 String gadget will reflect the VAR value.
                 See examples below.

          INPUT: TEXT/A     - Text of the TextBox gadget.

                 VAR/A      - Name of the variable where to store
                              the result.

                 VALUE      - (Optional) Starting value.

        RESULTS:

           NOTE: Even if you have chosen not to @{" Define " LINK define}
                 your variables, the VAR/A you want to use to store the
                 result must exists.

       EXAMPLES: - Text "Test 1" Test1 $Test1
                   Text "Test 2" Test2 $Test2

                   Will show "Test1" and "Test2" String gadgets and will
                   store the result in the Test1/2 vars.

       SEE ALSO: @{" Radio " LINK radio}
                 @{" Check " LINK check}
@endnode

@node "collectfiles" "PowerInstaller Commands: CollectFiles"

           NAME: CollectFiles

       SYNOPSIS: CollectFiles

    DESCRIPTION: Use this command to create an *internal* list
                 of all the files avaible inside an Archive.
                 This command takes some times, expecially on
                 slow machines, so you should use this command
                 with care, maybe at the beginning of your
                 script, in a BeginGUI/EndGUI executed only once
                 (use the command @{" NoPrevious " LINK noprovious}
                 for this purpose.


          INPUT: NONE


        RESULTS:

           NOTE: Even if you have chosen not to @{" Define " LINK define}
                 your variables, the VAR/A you want to use to store the
                 result must exists.

       EXAMPLES: - CollectFiles


                   Will show "Test1" and "Test2" String gadgets and will
                   store the result in the Test1/2 vars.

       SEE ALSO: @{" SetArchive  " LINK setarchive}
                 @{" SelectFiles " LINK selectfiles}
                 @{" SetFiles    " LINK setfiles}
@endnode

@node "SelectFiles" "PowerInstaller Commands: SelectFiles"

           NAME: SelectFiles

       SYNOPSIS: SelectFiles PATTERN/A

    DESCRIPTION: This command will generate a list of file names
                 based upon the internal list created using the
                 @{" CollectFiles " LINK collectfiles} command.
                 Every file is shown with an appropriate checkbox,
                 so the user can dynamically select what to install
                 and what not to install.

                 Since an archive may contain several files, you
                 have to provide a pattern in standard AmigaDOS
                 ReadArgs() format.

          INPUT: PATTERN        - (Needed) The pattern in standard
                                  AmigaDOS format.


        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - SelectFiles "Images/#?"

                   Will show a list of check boxes with all the files
                   present under the directory "Images" of your archive.

                 - SelectFiles "Images/#?.gif"

                   Same as above, but will show only files with the ".gif"
                   extension.

       SEE ALSO: @{" SetArchive   " LINK setarchive}
                 @{" CollectFiles " LINK collectfiles}
                 @{" SetFiles     " LINK setfiles}
@endnode

@node "Gadgets" "PowerInstaller Commands: Gadgets"

           NAME: Gadgets

       SYNOPSIS: Gadgets NOPREV/S,NOHELP/S,NOCANCEL/S,NONEXT/S

    DESCRIPTION: Use this command to remove some standard
                 Power Installer gadgets from the current GUI.

          INPUT: NOPREV     - If provided, the "< Prev" (Previous Page)
                              gadget will be hidden.

                 NOHELP     - If provided, the "Help" (Show Help)
                              gadget will be hidden.

                 NOCANCEL   - If provided, the "Cancel" (Cancel Installation)
                              gadget will be hidden.

                 NONEXT     - If provided, the "Next >" (Next Page)
                              gadget will be hidden.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - Gadgets NOPREV

                   The "< Prev" gadget will be hidden.


                 - Gadgets NOPREV NOHELP

                   Same as above, but the "Help" gadget will be hidden too.

       SEE ALSO: @{" SetArchive   " LINK setarchive}
                 @{" CollectFiles " LINK collectfiles}
                 @{" SetFiles     " LINK setfiles}
@endnode

@node "SetFiles" "PowerInstaller Commands: SetFiles"

           NAME: SetFiles

       SYNOPSIS: SetFiles FILTER/A,VALUE/A

    DESCRIPTION: With this command you'll be able to select/deselect
                 some files from being copied by @{" InstallFiles " LINK installfiles}
                 by simply providing a "0" or a "1" as the value parameter.
                 The SetFiles command work internally on the list you
                 previously created using @{" CollectFiles " LINK collectfiles}.


          INPUT: FILTER/A   - (Needed) File name matching, using the standard
                              AmigaDOS wilcards conventions.

                 VALUE/A    - (Needed) You can provide two different values:

                              0 - Every file matching the filter will not be
                                  copied (unless the user manually select it)

                              1 - Every file mathcing the filter will be copied
                                  (unless the user manually deselect it)

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - SetFiles "Images/#?" 0

                   During installation, all files inside the "Images/"
                   directory will be skipped (not copied).

                 - SelectFiles "Images/#?.gif" 1

                   Same as above, but will copy all the files ending with
                   ".gif" extension.

       SEE ALSO: @{" SetArchive   " LINK setarchive}
                 @{" CollectFiles " LINK collectfiles}
                 @{" SelectFiles  " LINK selectfiles}
@endnode

@node "dumpfiles" "PowerInstaller Commands: DumpFiles"

           NAME: DumpFiles

       SYNOPSIS: DumpFiles

    DESCRIPTION: This command is intended for debug purposes only.
                 With this command you can dump on the standard
                 console window the current files that will be
                 copied or skipped with the @{" InstallFiles " LINK installfiles}
                 command.


          INPUT: NONE

        RESULTS:

           NOTE: This is a DEBUG command only.
                 When PowerInstaller will be executed in USER mode, the
                 command will have no effect at all.

       EXAMPLES: - DumpFiles

                   Will dump all the files to be installed skipped.

       SEE ALSO: @{" SetArchive   " LINK setarchive}
                 @{" CollectFiles " LINK collectfiles}
                 @{" SelectFiles  " LINK selectfiles}
                 @{" InstallFiles " LINK installfiles}
@endnode

@node "CopyFile" "PowerInstaller Commands: CopyFile"

           NAME: CopyFile

       SYNOPSIS: CopyFile SRCFILE/A,DESTFILE/A,LIBRARY/S

    DESCRIPTION: Use this command to copy a single file
                 which does not belong to any archive.
                 This command will open also a Status Window
                 with just one progress bar related to the
                 current file in copy.

          INPUT: SRCFILE/A    - (Needed) Source file path and name.

                 DESTFILE/A   - (Needed) Destination file path and name.

                 LIBRARY/S    - Provide this switch if you are going to
                                copy a library.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - CopyFile "t:copyme" "$DestName"

                   Will copy "t:copyme" in the dir and name
                   inside the $DestName variable.


       SEE ALSO: @{" SetArchive   " LINK setarchive}
                 @{" CollectFiles " LINK collectfiles}
                 @{" SelectFiles  " LINK selectfiles}
                 @{" InstallFiles " LINK installfiles}
@endnode

@node "InstallFiles" "PowerInstaller Commands: InstallFiles"

           NAME: InstallFiles

       SYNOPSIS: InstallFiles PATH/A,LIBRARY/S

    DESCRIPTION: Use this command to perform a real software
                 installation.
                 This is the final command (step) you should call
                 to really install files on the user hard-drive.
                 Files are extracted from the archive you defined
                 with @{" SetArchive " LINK setarchive} and
                 @{" CollectFiles " LINK collectfiles}.
                 Eventually, these files may have been manipulated
                 with @{" SelectFiles " LINK selectfiles} and
                 @{" SetFiles " LINK setfiles}.


          INPUT: PATH/A       - (Needed) Path name where to install
                                files.

                 LIBRARY/S    - Provide this switch if you are going to
                                copy a library.

        RESULTS:

           NOTE: this command is smart enought to create all missing sub
                 directories.

       EXAMPLES: - InstallFiles $DestPath

                   Will install all files inside the $DestPath
                   directory.


       SEE ALSO: @{" SetArchive   " LINK setarchive}
                 @{" CollectFiles " LINK collectfiles}
                 @{" SelectFiles  " LINK selectfiles}
                 @{" CopyFile     " LINK copyfile}
@endnode

@node "SaveLog" "PowerInstaller Commands: SaveLog"

           NAME: SaveLog

       SYNOPSIS: SaveLog LOGNAME/A

    DESCRIPTION: Use this command to save current log into a file.
                 Power Installer keeps track of every operation
                 it performs in an internal log.
                 You can dump log's contents at any time using the
                 SaveLog command.

          INPUT: LOGNAME/A  - (Needed) File path and name.

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - SaveLog "ram:test.log"

                   Will save the internal log in "ram:test.log" file.

       SEE ALSO: @{" ClearLog " LINK clearlog}

@endnode

@node "ClearLog" "PowerInstaller Commands: ClearLog"

           NAME: ClearLog

       SYNOPSIS: ClearLog

    DESCRIPTION: This command simply clears ALL log messages in memory.

          INPUT:

        RESULTS:

       EXAMPLES: - ClearLog

                   Will clear logs in memory.

       SEE ALSO: @{" SaveLog " LINK savelog}

@endnode

@node "Execute" "PowerInstaller Commands: Execute"

           NAME: Execute

       SYNOPSIS: Execute COMMAND/A

    DESCRIPTION: With this command you can execute an external program.
                 The program is spawned syncronously, so PowerInstaller
                 will wait for your command to finish before continue
                 the installation process.

          INPUT: COMMAND/A  - The command you want to execute.

        RESULTS: execution return code will be saved in the 'Result'
                 variable.

       EXAMPLES: - Execute "c:dir sys: >ram:dirs"

                   Will call the dir command and save the output in "ram:dirs" file.
                   (Note: Result variable should be 0)

       SEE ALSO:

@endnode

